  <body>
    <header class="topbar">
      <nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary navigation">
        <a class="brand" href={`${base}`}>
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true">N</span>
          <span>Digital Use Symptom Networks</span>
        </a>
        <div class="nav-links">
          <a href="#abstract">Abstract</a>
          <a href="#findings">Findings</a>
          <a href="#figures">Figures</a>
          <a href="#methods">Methods</a>
          <a href="#materials">Materials</a>
        </div>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <div
      class="hero"
      style={`--hero-image: url("${base}figures/figure-1.png") center right / cover no-repeat; --hero-image-mobile: url("${base}figures/figure-1.png") center / cover no-repeat;`}
    >
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Adolescent mental health network study</p>
        <h1>Emotional Distress Drives Adolescent Digital Use Symptom Networks</h1>
        <p class="authors">
          Jing Zhang, Ling Zhang, Xizhe Zhang - Nanjing Children's Hospital and Nanjing
          Medical University
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Paper links">
          <a class="button primary" href={`${base}Manuscript.docx`} download>Download manuscript</a>
          <a class="button" href="#figures">View figures</a>
          <a class="button" href="#materials">Data and code availability</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <main>
      <div class="metrics" aria-label="Study scale">
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>10,356</strong>
          <span>Chinese adolescents in the baseline school cohort</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>6,092</strong>
          <span>matched adolescents across two waves about one year apart</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>147,506</strong>
          <span>young adults in the Global Mind Project triangulation sample</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>7,838</strong>
          <span>complete UK Millennium Cohort Study cases in replication</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section id="abstract">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Abstract</p>
            <h2>Emotion, not digital use, sits upstream.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            The paper combines item-level network control, longitudinal directionality,
            Bayesian directed graphs and two external triangulations to locate the upstream
            domain in adolescent digital-use-related symptom systems.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="abstract">
          <p class="abstract-text">
            Adolescent problematic digital use rarely stands alone; it sits within a
            broader system of emotional, sleep, diet, activity and behavioral symptoms,
            and which domain drives system-level change is unclear. In a school-based
            cohort of 10,356 Chinese adolescents, 6,092 matched across two waves, we
            combined item-level network control with longitudinal directionality. The
            baseline 104-node, six-domain network had a compact structural-control core:
            diet, behavior and emotion items dominated the static topology yet were
            distinct from the most central symptoms. Over time, emotional distress was
            the strongest upstream predictor of change across digital use, insomnia,
            behavior and diet, with behavior and activity downstream. A Bayesian directed
            graph converged independently on the same emotion-outgoing pattern. The
            emotional hub held across young adults in 240 countries, and a UK cohort
            reproduced the screen-sink pattern.
          </p>
          <ul class="finding-list">
            <li><strong>Keywords:</strong> emotional distress; adolescent digital use; symptom network; network control; cross-lagged panel network; Bayesian network</li>
            <li><strong>Running title:</strong> Emotion in adolescent digital use networks</li>
            <li><strong>Contact:</strong> zhangxizhe@njmu.edu.cn</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="findings">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Findings</p>
            <h2>Static structure and temporal priority separate cleanly.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            The study distinguishes nodes that dominate the instantaneous network topology
            from domains that predict later system-wide change.
          </p>
        </div>
        <ul class="finding-list">
          <li>
            <strong>A compact structural-control core sits outside centrality.</strong>
            Diet, behavior and emotion items govern the static topology, while several
            high-strength symptoms never enter the minimum dominating set.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Emotional distress is the strongest temporal driver.</strong>
            Across two waves, Wave-1 emotional distress predicts later increases across
            digital use, insomnia, behavior and diet more strongly than competing domains.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>A Bayesian directed graph converges on emotion outflow.</strong>
            Cross-sectional directional learning independently places emotional distress
            on the source side and agrees closely with the longitudinal CLPN.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The pattern travels across cohorts.</strong>
            The Global Mind Project reproduces an emotional hub across 240 countries, and
            the UK Millennium Cohort Study confirms screen-related behavior as downstream.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="figures">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Figures</p>
            <h2>Main results.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            The figure set moves from baseline topology to temporal directionality,
            independent directed checks and external replication.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="figure-stack">
          {mainFigures.map((figure) => (
            <article class="figure-card">
              <a class="figure-media" href={`${base}${figure.src}`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
                <img src={`${base}${figure.src}`} alt={`${figure.label}: ${figure.title}`} loading="lazy" />
              </a>
              <div class="figure-copy">
                <span class="figure-label">{figure.label}</span>
                <h3>{figure.title}</h3>
                <p>{figure.caption}</p>
              </div>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="methods">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Methods</p>
            <h2>Four complementary lenses.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            The design combines static graph control, longitudinal prediction, directed
            graphical modeling and external concept-level replication.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="methods-grid">
          <div class="method">
            <b>Network reconstruction</b>
            <p>
              Item scores were transformed with a Gaussian-copula transform and estimated
              using graphical Lasso with likelihood-based cross-validation.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="method">
            <b>Control analysis</b>
            <p>
              Minimum dominating sets, control frequency and module-control networks
              identified structural levers in the baseline symptom topology.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="method">
            <b>Cross-lagged panel network</b>
            <p>
              Wave-3 domain scores were regressed on all Wave-1 domains with robust
              standard errors and bootstrap confidence intervals for net directionality.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="method">
            <b>Bayesian directed graph</b>
            <p>
              A Hill-Climb BIC graph and bootstrap edge stability tested whether baseline
              dependencies supported the same directional ordering.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="method">
            <b>Global Mind Project</b>
            <p>
              A 240-country young-adult sample tested whether the emotional hub generalized
              across instruments, cultures and countries.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="method">
            <b>Millennium Cohort Study</b>
            <p>
              A UK longitudinal cohort tested whether internalizing distress and screen-use
              directionality recurred from age 14 to age 17.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="supplement">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Supplement</p>
            <h2>Additional figures.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            Supporting analyses cover matching, robustness, alternative directional checks,
            community structure, driver stability and null-model comparisons.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="supplement-grid">
          {supplementFigures.map((figure) => (
            <a href={`${base}${figure.src}`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
              <img src={`${base}${figure.src}`} alt={figure.label} loading="lazy" />
              <span>{figure.label}</span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="materials">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div>
            <p class="section-kicker">Materials</p>
            <h2>Availability.</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="lead">
            Public release is staged around ethics restrictions for individual-level data
            and open release of derived group-level artifacts upon acceptance.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="availability">
          <div class="availability-block">
            <h3>Data availability</h3>
            <p>
              Individual-level cohort data are restricted by ethics approval
              2022-KY095-02. Derived group-level matrices, coefficients, bootstrap outputs,
              Bayesian-network edge lists and machine-readable result tables are prepared
              for public release upon acceptance.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="availability-block">
            <h3>Code availability</h3>
            <p>
              Analysis scripts for network reconstruction, cross-lagged panel networks,
              Bayesian directed graphs, community detection, controllability analyses,
              null models and figure generation are prepared for release upon acceptance.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <footer>
      <span>
        Supported by NSFC-Jiangsu Joint Fund U24A20701 and HK RGC Strategic Target Grant
        STG1/M-501/23-N.
      </span>
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>
